body:
@occivink to run a GDB session for a running instance of `vim` all you should need to do is open a new terminal (running a shell as normal). The shell should be enough to keep your terminal from closing when/if you quit `gdb`. Run `sudo gdb`, and then attach to the `vim` process with `attach PID`.

Am I misunderstanding something?

To me the `--hold` flag is simply a way to avoid the shell, which is of marginal value to me, but does seem potentially useful. Alacritty's got a pretty minimal philosophy, which running commands in a useful way without a shell would fit into IMO.

@occivink I think I see what you mean now.

The way I'm able to get this to work is to open an instance of Alacritty, then run `alacritty&` from within the first terminal window to get another terminal window sharing the same process group. Find the `tty` of the second alacritty and then start `gdb vim` and point it to output on the second terminal with `tty /dev/pts/X`.

I think a shell only helps make this situation easier, but I suppose you may be concerned about the interaction of the shell, which a `--hold` option could help you avoid.
